# Study Guide
<table>
    <tr><th colspan=2>Unit 1: Ancient Civilizations</th></tr>
    <tr><th>1. What was the Neolithic Revolution</th>
        <td><u>The Neolithic Revolution was the process of humanity going from nomadic hunters and gatherers to farmers that settle in villages</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>2. Where did people settle to form civilization? Why?</th>
        <td><u>People settled in rivers vallies because when they flood, they create very fertile land.</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>3. What two rivers was Mesopotamia located on?</th>
        <td><u>Tigris and Euphrates</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>4. Describe Hammurabi's Code.
            <ol><li>What civilization created it?</li>
                <li>What were the laws and punishments based off of?</li>
                <li>Were the punishments the same for every level of society</li></ol></th>
        <td><ol><u><li>Egypt created Hammurabi's Code</li>
                <li>The laws and punishments were based off of property and damage to property</li>
                <li>The punishments were different for other levels of society</li></ol></u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>5. Egypt
            <ol><li>What river was Egypt located on?</li>
                <li>What position did the Pharoah have in Egyptian society?</li>
                <li>What did they base their 365 day calendar off?</li></ol></th>
        <td><ol><u><li>Egypt was based on the Nile river</li>
                <li>Pharoah had the position of ruler-god</li>
                <li>They based their 365 day calendar based off the flooding of the Nile river</li></ol></u></td></tr>
    <tr><th colspan=2>Unit 2: Greece and Rome</th></tr>
    <tr><th>6. Thinking about the government and military, compare Athens and Sparta?</th>
        <td><ol><li><b>Athens: </b><u>Athens was focused on technology, efficient government processes, and the pursuit of knowledge, however had a weaker army than Sparta</u></li>
                <li><b>Sparta: </b><u>Sparta wasn't necessarily focused on technology and advancement, but rather focuesed on a strong military</u></li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th>7. What were Alexander the Great's major accomplishments</th>
        <td><ol><li><u>Conquering both a lot of the Mediterranean and Egypt for Rome</u></li>
                <li><u>Spreading Hellenistic ideals</u></li>
                <li><b>Define Hellenism: </b><u>Roman ideals</u></li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th>8. What was the significance of Julius Caesar?</th>
        <td><ol><li><u>Used corruption to get his way to the top and become leader of Rome</u></li>
                <li><u>Invented the title of Caesar (ruler of Rome)</u></li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th>9. What aspects of Rome influenced future western societies?</th>
        <td><ol><li><u>Architecture</u></li>
                <li><u>Government</u></li>
                <li><u>Language</u></li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th colspan=2>Unit 3: Islam, Byzantine Empire, and Middle Ages</th></tr>
    <tr><th>10. Under which ruler did the Byzantine Empire reach its peak?</th>
        <td><u>Emperor Justinian</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>11. What is justinian's Code?</th>
        <td><u>Justinian's Code is a set of rules for the Byzantines to follow</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>12. Christianity<ol><li> 
    What caused the split of Christianity?</li>
                <li>What was it called?</li></ol></th>
        <td><u><ol><li>A plethora of reasons including corruption in the Catholic church</li>
                   <li>The Great Schism</li></ol></u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>13. Who was the founder of Islam?</th>
        <td><u>Muhammad</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>14. What two religions did Islam use as its foundation?</th>
        <td>Christianity and Judaism</th></tr>
    <tr><th>15. Early Middle Ages
            <ul><li>Feudalism
                <ol><li>Who was responsible for protecting the people?</li>
                    <li>Who had the most amount of power?</li></ol></li>
                <li>Characteristics
                <ol><li>Education</li>
                    <li>Greco-Roman culture</li>
                    <li>Language</li>
                    <li>Trade</li>
                    <li>Military</li>
                    <li>Religion</li></ol></li></ul></th>
        <td><u><b>ai</b>. The Knights were in charge of protecting the people<br><b>aii</b>. The land owners (lords) had the most power<br><b>bi</b>. Very little people were educated, illiteracy soared<br><b>bii</b>. Greco-roman culture went down a lot due to very little organization<br><b>biii</b>. Lots of different languages developed and Europe lost a common language<br><b>biv</b>. Trade went down drastically as there was little organization between kingdoms.<br><b>bv</b>. Military was less organized and each kingdom had their own military<br><b>bvi</b>. Almost all of medieval Europe was Catholic and religion was the only linking factor</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>What was the Crusades?</th>
        <td><u>The Crusades were a series of attempts to take back Jerusalem from Islam</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>What was the purpose of the Crusades?</th>
        <td><u>To take back the "holy lands" from Islam</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>Did the Catholic Church accomplish their goal?</th>
        <td><u>Nope</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>What impact did the crusades have on the power of the Catholic Church?</th>
        <td>Decrease in power</td></tr>
    <tr><th colspan=2>Unit 4: Age of Exploration</th></tr>
    <tr><th>17. What were the three motivations behind European exploration? Explain.</th>
        <td><ol><li><b>God</b>: Countries wanted to spread christianity/ catholicism</li>
                <li><b>Gold</b>: Countries wanted to profit off of their colonies</li>
                <li><b>Glory</b>: Many people came to colonies seeking leadership positions wwithin them</li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th>18. What was the significance of the following explorers' voyages?</th>
        <td><ol><li><b>Christopher Colombus</b>: "discovered" the Americas and paved the way for further exploration of the Americas</li>
                <li><b>Vasco da Gama</b>: First to discover a quick trade route to India.</li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th>19. Coumbian exchange
            <ol><li>What is it?</li>
                <li>How did it affect the Native Americans?</li>
                <li>How did it affect the Europeans?</li></ol></th>
        <td><u><b>a</b>. The Colombian Exchange is the economical and biological trade of goods between Europe and the Americas.<br><b>bi</b>. Lots of Native Americans died to disease and other factors<br><b>bii</b>. Lots of Native Americans were mistreated<br><b>ci</b>. Europe recieved a plethora of new goods<br><b>cii</b>. Europe profited massively because of the Colombian Exchange</td></u></tr>
    <tr><th>What was the "Middle Passage"?</th>
        <td><u>A route used to bring slaves across the Atlantic Ocean</u></td></tr>
    <tr><th>What TWO resources were significant to the Sub-Saharan trade?</th>
        <td>Gold and salt</td></tr>
    <tr><th>Who was...
            <ol><li>Mansa Musa</li>
                <li>Ibn Battuta</li></ol></th>
        <td><ol><li>Mansa Musa was the leader of Mali and is famous for his hajj to mecca</li>
                <li>Ibn Battuta was a famous Muslim traveller</li></ol></td></tr>
    <tr><th colspan=2>Unit 5: Renaissance and Reformation</th></tr>
    <tr><th>What is the literal meaning of the word "Renaissance"?</th>
        <td>A rebirth</td></tr>
    <tr><th>What two classical civilizations influenced the ideas of the Renaissance?</th>
        <td>Greece and Rome</td></tr>
    <tr><th>Define Humanism</th>
        <td>The belief in the abilities of the individual</td></tr>
    <tr><th>26. What were the causes of the Protestant reformation?
        <ul><li>Corruption
            <ol><li>Indulgences</li>
                <li>Lay investiture</li></ol></li>
            <li>Johann Gutenberg</li>
            <li>Martin Luther
            <ol><li>95 Theses</li></ol></li></ul></th>
        <td><ul><li><ol><li>The selling of forgiveness of sins</li>
                        <li>Paid positions in the Catholic church</li></ol></li>
                <li>Johann Gutenberg made the printing press which indirectly helped the Protestant reformation by allowing the information of the reformation to spread quickly</li>
                <li>Martin Luther helped advocate for the protestant reformation and even created the first protestant branch of Christianity
                <ol><li>The 95 theses were a list of 95 complaints nailed to the door of the Catholic church</li></ol></li></ul></td></tr>
